sentence: Broad-market exchange-traded funds, including SPY, IWM and IVV were all trading lower pre-market after a higher close.
Actively-traded PowerShares QQQ ( QQQ ) was also leaning lower.

U.S. stocks are pointing to a lower open ahead of Gross Domestic Product data that is expected to show that growth accelerated in the second quarter, leaving the way clear for the Federal Reserve to hike interest rates.
GDP is expected to expand 2.6%, according to a Reuters' survey.

In the meantime, the news flow was dominated by corporate earnings, with consumer giant Procter & Gamble ( PG ) reporting better-than-expected results, despite a hit to sales from foreign currency fluctuations.
Oil company ConocoPhillips ( COP ) also managed a beat, despite slumping commodity prices.

Consumer Staples Select Sector SPDR ( XLP ) edged up 0.08%, iShares Dow Jones US Consumer Goods ( IYK ), and Vanguard Consumer Staples ETF (VDC) were unchanged after rising to multi-year or record highs on Thursday.
Consumer Discretionary Select Sector SPDR (XLY) edged lower, SPDR S&P Retail (XRT) was leaning into the green, PowerShares Dynamic Retail (PMR) and Market Vectors Retail ETF (RTH) were unchanged.
Proctor & Gamble Thursday reported fiscal Q4 ended June 30 EPS above the street view, despite a YOY sales decline driven by FX.
The consumer-products giant reported non-GAAP core EPS of $1.00, up from $0.93 in the year earlier period, and above the street view of $0.95, as compiled by Capital IQ.
In GAAP terms, Proctor & Gamble reported net earnings from continuing operations of $0.22 per share, vs. $0.89 in the year-earlier period.

Technology Select Sector SPDR ETF (XLK), iShares Dow Jones US Technology ETF (IYW), iShares S&P North American Technology ETF (IGM) and iShares S&P North American Technology-Software Index (IGV) were all inactive pre-market and all closed higher Wednesday.
SPDR S&P International Technology Sector ETF (IPK) was flat and bucked the trend to close lower.
Semiconductor ETFs, SPDR S&P Semiconductor (XSD) was flat, while Semiconductor Sector Index Fund (SOXX) was edging lower.
T-Mobile US (TMUS) shares rose over 5% in recent pre-market trade after reporting better than expected Q2 revenue and raising its guidance for subscribers in 2015.
The mobile network provider said its net income fell to $361 million or $0.42 per share from $391 million or $0.48 a year earlier, exceeding the $0.22 average estimate, if comparable.
Revenue rose 14% to $8.2 billion and beat the $7.96 billion consensus estimate.
Select Financial Sector SPDRs (XLF) fell 0.12%.
Direxion Daily Financial Bull 3X shares (FAS) and Direxion Daily Financial Bear 3X Shares (FAZ) were unchanged.
Education Realty Trust (EDR), a real estate investment trust, reported early Thursday its Q2 2015 core funds from operations lower than the Street consensus, while revenues came in higher.
Net income for the quarter was $2.9 million, or $0.06 per share; compared to a net loss of $8.8 million, or $0.23 per share in Q2 2014.
Industrial ETFs iShares Trust Dow Jones U.S. Industrial Sector Index Fund (IYJ) and Vanguard Industrials (VIS) were inactive, while Select Sector SPDR-Industrial (XLI) were in the positive territory.
Timken Company (The), a maker of bearings, posted Q2 earnings shy of forecasts, while revenue and its 2015 earnings guidance were below the mark.
Adjusted net income was $49.1 million or $0.57 per diluted share, down from $59.4 million or $0.65 per diluted share for the same period in 2014 and a penny below analysts' estimates.
Net income from continuing operations was $36.7 million or $0.43 per diluted share for the quarter, versus $56.5 million or $0.61 per diluted share a year ago.
Sales fell 8% to $728 million, below expectations for $739.3 million.
Dow Jones U.S. Energy Fund (IYE) was flat and Energy Select Sector SPDR (XLE) was up 0.11%.

ConocoPhillips ( COP ) shares were higher over 2% in recent pre-market trade after reporting better-than-expected earnings and as it lowered its capital expenditure budget while sales fell to well below the Street's view.
The exploration and production company said adjusted earnings dropped to $0.07 per share from $1.61 a year ago, exceeding the $0.04 average estimate from analysts polled by Capital IQ.
The drop was primarily due to lower realized prices, partially offset by higher licensing revenues.
Revenue fell to $8.66 billion from $14.7 billion a year ago, missing the $9.55 billion consensus estimate.
Crude was up 0.4%; United States Oil Fund (USO) fell 0.7%.
Natural gas was up 1.2% and United States Natural Gas Fund (UNG) was up 0.66%.
Gold was down 0.7%, and SPDR Gold Trust (GLD) dropped 1%.
Health Care SPDR (XLV) was down 0.1%, iShares Dow Jones US Healthcare (IYH) was flat and Vanguard Health Care ETF (VHT) was tipping into the red.
Meanwhile, Biotech ETF iShares NASDAQ Biotechnology Index (IBB) was heading higher.
Navidea Biopharmaceuticals (NAVB) says Q2 sales were $2.9 million, above the CapIQ mean for $2 million.
Net loss was $0.06 per share, worse than expectations for a $0.04 loss.
